  "prompt": "Why don't Indian parents allow their daughter to marry a guy from a different caste?",
  "response": "The reasons for caste-based marriage restrictions in Indian families are complex and rooted in historical, social, and cultural factors:\n\n1. Traditional beliefs\n- Maintaining cultural and social purity\n- Preserving family lineage and heritage\n- Belief in caste-based social hierarchy\n\n2. Social pressures\n- Fear of social stigma and rejection\n- Community and family reputation\n- Pressure from extended family and society\n\n3. Economic considerations\n- Concerns about social and economic status\n- Inheritance and property rights\n- Potential loss of social connections\n\n4. Cultural practices\n- Long-standing societal norms\n- Arranged marriage traditions\n- Perceived compatibility based on caste background\n\n5. Historical conditioning\n- Centuries of caste-based social stratification\n- Ingrained social conditioning\n- Generational transmission of caste-based thinking\n\n6. Religious interpretations\n- Some religious texts historically supported caste distinctions\n- Conservative religious interpretations\n\n7. Lack of exposure and education\n- Limited understanding of social equality\n- Limited interaction with diverse communities\n\nWhile these attitudes persist, many urban, educated Indians are challenging these traditional views and promoting inter-caste marriages. Younger generations are increasingly rejecting rigid caste-based marriage restrictions.\n\nNote: These are generalized observations and individual family perspectives can vary significantly.",
